            Content, if provided, is <gloss xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xml:id="καταρράκτην_1590"> (from <quote xml:lang="grc">ῥάσσω</quote> to strike hard, or dash, cp. 1503), lit. <quote xml:lang="eng">"dashing or rushing down"</quote> ; Strabo 10. 640 <quote xml:lang="grc">τηρήσας καταρράκτην ὄμβρον</quote> : here, of a cleft <emph>descending abruptly</emph> into the ground. Strabo applies the word to the cataracts of the Nile (called <quote xml:lang="grc">κατάδουποι</quote> by Her.): in this sense it is usu. spelt with one <quote xml:lang="grc">ρ</quote> , as if from <quote xml:lang="grc">καταράσσω</quote> : so Lucan 10. 317 <quote xml:lang="lat">praecipites cataractae.</quote> Cp. <cit> <bibl n="Plut. Ad Princ. 781e" ref="Plut. Ad Princ. 781e"> Plut. <title>Mor.</title> 781 E</bibl> <quote xml:lang="grc">οἴκημα θύραν ἔχον ἐπιρρακτήν</quote> </cit>, a room with a trap-door in it: so too <title>Arat.</title> 26 <quote xml:lang="grc">θύρᾳ καταρρακτῇ</quote> . The <foreign xml:lang="lat">v.l.</foreign> <quote xml:lang="grc">καταφράκτην</quote> (Suidas) is worthless.</gloss>, filename ../../PerseusDL/canonical_pdlrefwk/data/viaf2603144/viaf002/viaf2603144.viaf002.perseus-eng1.xml.
            
