XML context, if available, is: <gloss xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xml:id="μὴ_κρατεῖς_839">, do not give orders in matters where you are not master. <quote xml:lang="grc">ἃ</quote> is not for <quote xml:lang="grc">ὧν</quote> , but is cogn. accus. (or acc. of respect), as <cit> <bibl n="Soph. OT 1522" ref="urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0011.tlg004:1522"> <title>O. T.</title> 1522</bibl> <quote xml:lang="grc">πάντα μὴ βούλου κρατεῖν· | καὶ γὰρ ἁκράτησας</quote> </cit>. For the gen. in a like sense cp. <cit> <bibl n="Hdt. 9.16" ref="Hdt. 9.16">Her. 9.16</bibl> <quote xml:lang="grc">ἐχθίστη...ὀδύνη..., πολλὰ φρονέοντα μηδενὸς κρατέειν</quote> </cit>, to have many presentiments, and power over nothing. <cit> <bibl n="Soph. Ant. 664" ref="Soph. Ant. 664"> <title>Ant.</title> 664</bibl> <quote xml:lang="grc">τοὐπιτάσσειν τοῖς κρατύνουσιν</quote> </cit>, to dictate to one's masters. <cit> <bibl n="Theoc. 15" ref="Theoc. 15">Theocr. 15. 90</bibl> <quote xml:lang="grc">πασάμενος ἐπίτασσε</quote> </cit>(wait till you are our master before you give us orders).</gloss>

