            Content, if provided, is <gloss xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xml:id="Διρκαίων_103">. The Dircè was on the w. of Thebes, the Ismenus on the E. : between them flowed the less famous Strophia: <cit> <bibl n="Call. Del. 76">Callim. <title>Hymn Del.</title> 76</bibl> <quote xml:lang="grc">Δίρκη τε Στροφίη τε μελαμψηφῖδος ἔχουσαι | )Ισμηνοῦ χέρα πατρός</quote> </cit> (alluding to their common source S. of the town). Though the Ismenus, as the eastern stream, would have been more appropriately named here, the Dircè is preferred, as the representative river of Thebes: so Pindar, ‘the Dircaean swan,’ expresses ‘at Thebes and at Sparta’ by <quote xml:lang="grc">ῥεέθροισί τε Δίρκας...καὶ παρ’ Εὐρώτᾳ</quote> ( <ref n="Pind. I. 1">Pind. <title>Isthm.</title> 1. 29</ref>). <ref n="Soph. Ant. 844">Cp. 844</ref>. </gloss>, filename ../../PerseusDL/canonical_pdlrefwk/data/viaf2603144/viaf003/viaf2603144.viaf003.perseus-eng1.xml.
            
