XML context, if available, is: <gloss xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xml:id="νηλίπους_349">: schol. <quote xml:lang="grc">α·νυπόδητος</quote> . <cit> <bibl n="Apollon. 3.646" ref="Apollon. 3.646">Apoll. Rhod. 3. 646</bibl> <quote xml:lang="grc">νήλιπος, οἰέανος</quote> </cit>(shoeless, with only a tunic): <cit> <bibl n="Theoc. 4" ref="Theoc. 4">Theocr. 4. 56</bibl> <quote xml:lang="grc">εἰς ὄρος ὅκχ’ ἕρπῃς, μὴ ἀνάλιπος ἔρχεο, Βάττε</quote> </cit>: where schol. <quote xml:lang="grc">ἦλιψ γὰρ τὸ ὑπόδημα</quote> . If the word really comes from an <quote xml:lang="grc">ἦλιψ</quote> (of which there is no other trace), then <foreign xml:lang="grc">νηλίπους</foreign> (used also by <ref>Lycophron 635</ref> , who, however, may have followed Soph.) is less correct than <quote xml:lang="grc">νήλιπος</quote> , which Blomfield ( <ref n="Aesch. PB 248"> Aesch. <title>PV</title> 248</ref>) wished to restore here. <ref>Eustathius 787. 52</ref> derives <quote xml:lang="grc">νήλιπος</quote> from <quote xml:lang="grc">λίπος</quote> (fat, unguent), explaining it by <quote xml:lang="grc">αὐχμηρὸς καὶ ἀλιπής</quote> ( <quote xml:lang="eng">"unkempt"</quote> ). </gloss>

